{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Network Performance Metrics\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 How Do Loss and Delay Occur?\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Packets queue in router buffers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Packet arrival rate to the link exceeds the output link capacity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Packets queue, wait for turn\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Arriving packets are dropped if there are no free buffers\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Transmission delay is a function of bandwidth. If you have a higher bandwidth you can push things onto the connection faster.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There's also queueing delay.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Four Sources of Packet Delay\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1.\tx360\tab processing delay\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab check bit errors\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab copy over to output queue\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab determine output link\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab usually negligible\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2.\tx360\tab queueing\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab time waiting at output link for transmission\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab depend on congestion level of route\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab depend on number of hops (routers)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3.\tx360\tab propagation delay\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab function of the distance\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab = d / s (length of link / propagation speed in medium)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab s e.g. 2 * 10^8 m/s in copper\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab can't change the distance or the speed of light easily, so have no control over this\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4.\tx360\tab transmission delay\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab L / R\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab L is the packet length\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab R is the link bandwidth\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Size of what you're sending affects whether transmission delay or propagation delay is most relevant.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Nodal delay = processing delay + queueing delay + transmission delay + propagation delay\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Queueing Delay\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Traffic intensity = {\f1 La/R} where:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab L is the packet length\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a is the average packet arrival rate\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab R is the link bandwidth\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Packet Loss\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Packets get dropped when router queues fill up. Lost packets may be resent from the source, or not.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Throughput\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Throughput is end-to-end.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 It's the rate (bits per time unit) at which bits are transferred between sender and receiver.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab instantaneous is the rate at a given point in time\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab average is the rate over a longer period of time\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Network\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Common enough to have questions where you're given a network and you have to work out the delay.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Start by writing this equation: {\f1 D = T + P + Q} (processing delay is ignored as it's usually not significant).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Next think about which of these you need to calculate\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab If there are no routers there's no queueing delay\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab If we're not told how long the wire is we can't calculate the propagation delay\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Throughput\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 What is the average end to end throughput when Rs < Rc? It's Rs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When Rc < Rs? It's Rc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The bottleneck link is the link on the end to end path that has the lowest available data rate. That one determines your throughput.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Internet Scenario\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The per-connection end-to-end throughput is min(Rs, Rc, R/10), where R is the shared link in the middle for 10 connections. In practice it's nearly always Rc.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Network Protocol Architecture\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Today's networks are very complicated (lots of different types of connections, lots of connections), and have very different applications (web, streaming, VoIP, gaming).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To deal with complexity:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab We need to cope with heterogeneity of function and requirements, including for example:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab network speed, errors, latency\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab application security, reliability, quality of service\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Need to facilitate evolution of network elements and applications\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab upgrade to better technology\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab adapt to changing needs\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs32 Layered Architectures\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is somewhat similar to abstraction in OOP.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Similar network functions are grouped together into distinct layers\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Layers are organised in a stack, representing increasing functionality\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab And the dependency of a layer on the layer below\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Layering is an abstraction that enforces modularity\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Makes it easier to change the network functions\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Each layer implements a service via its own internal-layer actions, relying on services provided by the layer below.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 Internet Protocol Architecture\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5.\tx360\tab Application layer (L5)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab This does application-specific functions (e.g. http, email, DNS, BitTorrent)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6.\tx360\tab Transport layer (L4)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Common end-to-end delivery functions like reliability, security, e.g. TCP\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 7.\tx360\tab Network layer (L3)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Core network functions for delivery of a packet across multiple links to the destination, e.g. IP (Internet Protocol)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab There's only one protocol here (hourglass structure)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 8.\tx360\tab Link layer (L2)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Functions to deliver a packet across a single link, such as for error detection, e.g. WiFi\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 9.\tx360\tab Physical layer (L1)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Defines the operation of a physical communication medium e.g. optical fibre\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs28 ISO/OSI Reference Model\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This is not widely used. It's considered to be a bit too complicated.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 7.\tx360\tab Application\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 8.\tx360\tab Presentation\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Allow applications to interpret meaning of data, e.g. encryption, compression, machine-specific conventions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab This stuff is done in the application layer in IPA\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 9.\tx360\tab Session\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Synchronisation, checkpointing, recovery of data exchange\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Also implemented in application layer in IPA\sa180\par}
